ğŸ§  1. What Is the Stream API?
============================
â¤ The Stream API is a functional programming tool introduced in Java 8
for processing collections of data (like List, Set, Map, arrays, etc.) in a declarative and efficient way.

    Instead of writing loops and if conditions manually,
    Stream allows you to express data transformations in a pipeline of operations.


ğŸ” 2. Why Stream API?
======================
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
| Traditional Approach                  | Stream API Approach             |
| ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| External Iteration (e.g., `for` loop) | Internal Iteration              |
| Imperative style                      | Declarative style               |
| Harder to parallelize                 | Easy parallel processing        |
| Mutates data                          | Non-mutating (functional style) |
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------


âš™ï¸ 3. Core Concepts of Stream API
======================================
3.1 Stream Definition
    A Stream represents a sequence of elements supporting sequential and parallel operations.

3.2 Stream Characteristics:
    - Not a data structure (does not store data)
    - Can only be used once
    - Lazy evaluation â€” operations are executed only when a terminal operation is called
    - Supports pipelined operations
    - Can be sequential or parallel



ğŸ§© 4. Stream Pipeline Components
==================================
A Stream pipeline has three parts:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Part                           | Description                                  | Example                                |
| ------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| 1. Source                      | Collection, array, generator, or I/O channel | `list.stream()`                        |
| 2. Intermediate Operations     | Transform or filter data                     | `.filter()`, `.map()`, `.sorted()`     |
| 3. Terminal Operation          | Produces a result or side-effect             | `.collect()`, `.forEach()`, `.count()` |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



